Executive Summary
=================

Context engineering is a rapidly maturing discipline in AI development that focuses on the **systematic design and management of the information contexts** provided to [large language models (LLMs)](https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/key-innovations-behind-chatgpt) and other AI systems. Unlike traditional *prompt engineering*, which emphasizes crafting individual prompts or instructions for AI models, context engineering involves curating, integrating, and orchestrating diverse data sources, memory mechanisms, and environmental signals so that AI systems have the relevant *background* needed to perform reliably and accurately on complex tasks. This report provides an in-depth exploration of context engineering, covering definitions, historical background, technical components, current practices, and future directions.

Key findings and points include:

* **Definition and Scope:** Context engineering is commonly defined as designing and structuring relevant data, workflows, and environments so that AI systems can understand user intent and make better, context-rich decisions ([[1]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20defines%20context%20engineering%20as,without%20relying%20on%20manual%20prompts "Highlights: Gartner defines context engineering as,without relying on manual prompts")) ([[2]](https://www.datacamp.com/blog/context-engineering#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20the%20practice,before%20it%20generates%20a%20response "Highlights: Context engineering is the practice,before it generates a response")). It goes beyond prompt writing to include building pipelines for conversation history, external documents, user profiles, real-time data, and tools integration ([[2]](https://www.datacamp.com/blog/context-engineering#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20the%20practice,before%20it%20generates%20a%20response "Highlights: Context engineering is the practice,before it generates a response")) ([[1]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20defines%20context%20engineering%20as,without%20relying%20on%20manual%20prompts "Highlights: Gartner defines context engineering as,without relying on manual prompts")). Gartner describes it as delivering “contextual, enterprise-aligned outcomes — without relying on manual prompts” ([[1]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20defines%20context%20engineering%20as,without%20relying%20on%20manual%20prompts "Highlights: Gartner defines context engineering as,without relying on manual prompts")).
* **Motivation:** AI systems often fail due to insufficient or irrelevant context, not model flaws. Industry data suggest over *40% of AI project failures* stem from poor or irrelevant context inputs ([[3]](https://contextengineering.ai/blog/what-is-context-engineering/#:~:text=This%20is%20the%20central%20challenge,billion%20dollar%20problem "Highlights: This is the central challenge,billion dollar problem")) ([[1]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20defines%20context%20engineering%20as,without%20relying%20on%20manual%20prompts "Highlights: Gartner defines context engineering as,without relying on manual prompts")). High-profile voices (e.g. Shopify’s CEO Tobi Lütke and AI researcher Andrej Karpathy) emphasize that “providing all the necessary context” is the core skill in AI tool building ([[4]](https://blog.getzep.com/what-is-context-engineering/#:~:text=The%20change%20has%20gotten%20attention,the%20LLM%20can%20solve%20it "Highlights: The change has gotten attention,the LLM can solve it")) ([[5]](https://blog.getzep.com/what-is-context-engineering/#:~:text=Context%20engineering%2C%20at%20its%20core%2C,perform%20consistently%20across%20varied%20scenarios "Highlights: Context engineering, at its core,,perform consistently across varied scenarios")). As Gartner notes, context gaps lead to hallucinations and misalignment; context engineering is critical for reducing errors and improving AI reliability ([[6]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20research%20backs%20up%20the,context%20to%20improve%20AI%20results "Highlights: Gartner research backs up the,context to improve AI results")) ([[7]](https://www.gartner.com/en/documents/6904266#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20becoming%20critical,efficiency%20and%20continuous%20context%20validation "Highlights: Context engineering is becoming critical,efficiency and continuous context validation")).
* **Techniques and Tools:** Core techniques include **Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)** (connecting LLMs to external knowledge bases or documents), **memory architectures** (persistent or episodic memory mechanisms to retain information across interactions), **knowledge graphs** and **vector databases** (for structured context retrieval), and **protocols** like the *Model Context Protocol (MCP)* for tool integration. In December 2025, Anthropic donated MCP to the newly formed **Agentic AI Foundation (AAIF)** under the Linux Foundation, co-founded by Anthropic, Block, and OpenAI with support from Google, Microsoft, AWS, and Cloudflare ([[8]](https://www.anthropic.com/news/donating-the-model-context-protocol-and-establishing-of-the-agentic-ai-foundation)), cementing MCP as the de facto industry standard with over 97 million monthly SDK downloads. Research continues to advance formal frameworks (e.g. *Directed Information γ-covering* for optimal context selection ([[9]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.00079#:~:text=We%20introduce%20%5Ctextbf%7BDirected%20Information%20%24%5Cgamma%24,and%20enforces%20a%20diversity%20margin "Highlights: We introduce \textbf{Directed Information $\gamma$,and enforces a diversity margin"))) and biologically-inspired memory systems (*Cognitive Workspace* enabling active memory management ([[10]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.13171#:~:text=Large%20Language%20Models%20,developments%20reveals%20that%20while%20techniques "Highlights: Large Language Models ,developments reveals that while techniques")) ([[11]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.13171#:~:text=achieves%20an%20average%2058.6,retrieval%20to%20genuine%20cognitive%20augmentation "Highlights: achieves an average 58.6,retrieval to genuine cognitive augmentation"))). [Multi-agent LLM systems](https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/ai-agents-pharmacovigilance) also rely on context engineering to coordinate tasks, as shown in a code-assistant framework that combines intent translation, semantic retrieval, document synthesis, and specialized tool agents ([[12]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.08322#:~:text=context%20engineering%20workflow%20that%20combines,shot%20success%20rates%20and%20better "Highlights: context engineering workflow that combines,shot success rates and better")).
* **[Case Studies](/resources/case-studies):** Real-world examples demonstrate the impact of context engineering. A [telecommunication chatbot](https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/ai-chatbots-healthcare) that was integrated with customer databases, conversation memory, and dynamic instructions saw **significantly higher satisfaction** and lower escalation rates ([[13]](https://bradenkelley.com/2025/08/why-context-engineering-is-the-next-frontier-in-ai/#:~:text=The%20context,to%20understand%20the%20customer%E2%80%99s%20individual "Highlights: The context,to understand the customer’s individual")). In healthcare, an experimental [AI diagnostic tool for rare diseases](https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/llm-physician-diagnostic-accuracy) that was fed comprehensive patient history, lifestyle data, and medical literature achieved higher accuracy and timeliness than models without full context ([[14]](https://bradenkelley.com/2025/08/why-context-engineering-is-the-next-frontier-in-ai/#:~:text=The%20Impact%3A "Highlights: The Impact:")). [Enterprise adoption](https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/astrazeneca-chatgpt-case-study) is also highlighted by Gartner’s emphasis that organizations should appoint context-engineering teams and invest in **context-aware architectures** to drive ROI ([[6]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20research%20backs%20up%20the,context%20to%20improve%20AI%20results "Highlights: Gartner research backs up the,context to improve AI results")) ([[7]](https://www.gartner.com/en/documents/6904266#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20becoming%20critical,efficiency%20and%20continuous%20context%20validation "Highlights: Context engineering is becoming critical,efficiency and continuous context validation")).
* **Challenges and Risks:** Managing context poses new challenges. Overloading models can cause noise, so context must be filtered and summarized appropriately. [Data privacy and quality](https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/secure-chatgpt-azure-integration) become critical when feeding sensitive or real-time context ([[15]](https://www.techradar.com/computing/artificial-intelligence/chatgpt-can-remember-more-about-you-than-ever-before-should-you-be-worried#:~:text=OpenAI%20has%20significantly%20upgraded%20ChatGPT%E2%80%99s,to%20make%20AI%20interactions%20more "Highlights: OpenAI has significantly upgraded ChatGPT’s,to make AI interactions more")) ([[16]](https://www.axios.com/2025/07/11/chatgpt-memory-update#:~:text=OpenAI%20is%20enhancing%20ChatGPT%27s%20memory,risks%20unintended%20or%20awkward%20interactions "Highlights: OpenAI is enhancing ChatGPT's memory,risks unintended or awkward interactions")). Ongoing monitoring and human oversight are needed, as context is fluid (e.g. user goals change, world events occur) ([[17]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Context%20is%20constantly%20changing%2C%20so,keep%20AI%20current "Highlights: Context is constantly changing, so,keep AI current")) ([[18]](https://bradenkelley.com/2025/08/why-context-engineering-is-the-next-frontier-in-ai/#:~:text=,This%20involves "Highlights: ,This involves")). Moreover, complex context pipelines may introduce new points of failure or bias, requiring robust governance.
* **Future Directions:** The field is evolving rapidly in 2026. New techniques for **extended context memory** (e.g. M+ LLM extending memory to 160K tokens ([[19]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.00592#:~:text=augmented%20model%20based%20on%20MemoryLLM,tokens%20with%20similar%20GPU%20memory "Highlights: augmented model based on MemoryLLM,tokens with similar GPU memory"))), active memory frameworks that model human cognition ([[10]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.13171#:~:text=Large%20Language%20Models%20,developments%20reveals%20that%20while%20techniques "Highlights: Large Language Models ,developments reveals that while techniques")) ([[11]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.13171#:~:text=achieves%20an%20average%2058.6,retrieval%20to%20genuine%20cognitive%20augmentation "Highlights: achieves an average 58.6,retrieval to genuine cognitive augmentation")), and nuanced context tuning for RAG systems ([[9]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.00079#:~:text=We%20introduce%20%5Ctextbf%7BDirected%20Information%20%24%5Cgamma%24,and%20enforces%20a%20diversity%20margin "Highlights: We introduce \textbf{Directed Information $\gamma$,and enforces a diversity margin")) are maturing. Classical RAG is evolving into broader "context engines" with intelligent retrieval at their core, while million-token context windows and agentic AI architectures are rewriting retrieval strategies. MCP's standardization under the Linux Foundation ([[8]](https://www.anthropic.com/news/donating-the-model-context-protocol-and-establishing-of-the-agentic-ai-foundation)) confirms that context engineering is becoming as fundamental as database or API design. Gartner predicts that 40% of enterprise apps will feature task-specific AI agents by late 2026 ([[20]](https://www.gartner.com/en/newsroom/press-releases/2025-08-26-gartner-predicts-40-percent-of-enterprise-apps-will-feature-task-specific-ai-agents-by-2026-up-from-less-than-5-percent-in-2025)), all requiring sophisticated context engineering, and that context engineering will supplant prompt engineering as a core capability for AI success ([[1]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20defines%20context%20engineering%20as,without%20relying%20on%20manual%20prompts "Highlights: Gartner defines context engineering as,without relying on manual prompts")) ([[21]](https://www.gartner.com/en/documents/6781234#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20in%2C%20and,and%20lasting%20impact%20of%20AI "Highlights: Context engineering is in, and,and lasting impact of AI")).

This report elaborates on these points with extensive citations. We begin with background on prompting and the emergence of context engineering, then delve into technical components (context sources, retrieval, memory, protocols), present case studies and data, and conclude with implications and future research directions.

Introduction and Background
===========================

The Role of Context in Intelligence
-----------------------------------

In both human cognition and AI, **context** is crucial for understanding. Context encompasses all relevant information beyond an isolated query: history of the conversation, user preferences, world knowledge, and situational cues like time and location.For humans, context allows us to disambiguate language, infer intent, and apply commonsense. For AI, especially language models, providing adequate context is essential to generate accurate and relevant responses. Without context, even the most advanced LLM can produce nonsensical or harmful outputs.

**Historical Parallel:** The importance of context has long been recognized in cognitive science. Theories such as Gibbs’ context model of language use and earlier work on context-dependent word meanings emphasize that meaning is relational. In computing, notions of context have appeared in fields like ubiquitous computing (context-aware systems), dialogue systems (state tracking), and cognitive architectures.

**In AI Evolution:** Early AI systems often operated with limited context. Early chatbots (e.g., ELIZA) had minimal memory. Statistical NLP systems typically used fixed window contexts for language modeling. With neural models, RNNs and transformers allowed larger contexts, but initially only for a single prompt. As large language models (LLMs) grew powerful, developers realized a new challenge: these models can generate fluent text, but lack situational awareness without additional information.

Emergence of Prompt vs Context Engineering
------------------------------------------

When GPT-3 and similar models debuted (2020-2021), the practice of **prompt engineering** emerged: carefully crafting the textual prompt fed to the model to elicit desired behavior. Prompt engineering involves writing instructions, providing examples, and fine-tuning the phrasing. This was sufficient for simple use-cases, but as AI applications became more sophisticated, practitioners encountered limitations.

By 2024, industry leaders began emphasizing the need to shift focus from just prompts to the *broader context* provided to models. Influencers like Andrej Karpathy and organizations like Gartner declared that “prompt engineering is out” and “context engineering is in” ([[1]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20defines%20context%20engineering%20as,without%20relying%20on%20manual%20prompts "Highlights: Gartner defines context engineering as,without relying on manual prompts")) ([[21]](https://www.gartner.com/en/documents/6781234#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20in%2C%20and,and%20lasting%20impact%20of%20AI "Highlights: Context engineering is in, and,and lasting impact of AI")). The term **”context engineering”** itself began to circulate in 2024–2025, often credited to Karpathy’s talks (e.g. *”Software is Changing (Again)” talk at YC’s AI School*). It reflects a fundamental shift: instead of *only* improving the wording of prompts, developers are now building entire pipelines and environments around the AI. As one data scientist put it, context engineering is like “stocking the pantry, prepping the ingredients” for the AI chef ([[22]](https://medium.com/packt-hub/beyond-prompts-the-rise-of-context-engineering-adc3310a3917#:~:text=Beyond%20Prompts%3A%20The%20Rise%20of,ingredients%2C%20and%20ensuring%20the%20model "Highlights: Beyond Prompts: The Rise of,ingredients, and ensuring the model")). By early 2026, the shift is well established: context engineering is widely recognized as the core discipline underlying production-grade AI systems, with dedicated guides, tooling, and enterprise adoption strategies now commonplace ([[23]](https://towardsai.net/p/machine-learning/context-engineering-the-6-techniques-that-actually-matter-in-2026-a-comprehensive-guide)).

Defining Context Engineering
----------------------------

**Gartner Definition:** According to Gartner, *“Context engineering”* is defined as *“designing and structuring the relevant data, workflows and environment so AI systems can understand intent, make better decisions and deliver contextual, enterprise-aligned outcomes — without relying on manual prompts.”* ([[1]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20defines%20context%20engineering%20as,without%20relying%20on%20manual%20prompts "Highlights: Gartner defines context engineering as,without relying on manual prompts")). The emphasis here is on an *engineering discipline* of assembling **data and processes** rather than crafting single prompts.

**Industry Perspective:** An industry blog explains context engineering as the *“practice of designing systems that decide what information an AI model sees before it generates a response”* ([[2]](https://www.datacamp.com/blog/context-engineering#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20the%20practice,before%20it%20generates%20a%20response "Highlights: Context engineering is the practice,before it generates a response")). In other words, rather than simply writing a clever question, context engineers build systems that gather conversation history, user data, documents, and tools, and format them into the model’s context window. Another author analogizes a model to a surgeon: prompts are the operation order, but context engineering provides the patient’s full medical records, imaging scans, and instruments ([[24]](https://contextengineering.ai/blog/what-is-context-engineering/#:~:text=Think%20of%20an%20LLM%20as,the%20surgeon%E2%80%99s%20skill%20is%20useless "Highlights: Think of an LLM as,the surgeon’s skill is useless")).

**Key Components:** As this definition suggests, context engineering involves multiple components:

* **Data Sources:** Integration of relevant documents, database queries, sensor data, knowledge bases, etc., tailored to the task.
* **Memory:** Mechanisms to retain information across interactions, so the model can recall past user details or events.
* **Dynamic Workflows:** Automated pipelines that fetch, filter, and update context in real time.
* **Protocols & Tooling:** Standard interfaces (like APIs or emerging protocols) that let models use external tools (search engines, calculators, etc.) as context providers.
* **Governance & Feedback:** Processes to validate and refine context (monitoring, human-in-the-loop corrections, data validation).

In sum, context engineering treats the AI system as an integrated application, where the *environment* and *data flow* are as important as the LLM itself.

The Shift from Prompt Engineering to Context Engineering
========================================================

The realization that context matters more than prompt wording is supported by multiple perspectives:

* **Limitations of Prompt Engineering:** While creative prompts can coax better outputs, they cannot compensate once the model exhausts its inherent knowledge or lacks situational data. Although LLM context windows have expanded dramatically — from early 4K–16K tokens to 128K–200K tokens (GPT-4o, Claude 3.5) and even 1–2 million tokens (Gemini 1.5, Claude 3.5 extended) — simply flooding them with information can dilute important context and degrade performance through what researchers call "context rot." Developers found that making prompts longer or trickier yields diminishing returns and still leads to errors when background facts are poorly curated.
* **Gartner’s View:** In July 2025, Gartner explicitly stated: *“Context engineering is in, and prompt engineering is out. AI leaders must prioritize context over prompts… This is critical for the relevance, adaptability, and lasting impact of AI.”* ([[21]](https://www.gartner.com/en/documents/6781234#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20in%2C%20and,and%20lasting%20impact%20of%20AI "Highlights: Context engineering is in, and,and lasting impact of AI")). Gartner’s research suggests that organizations moving to *context-rich* AI solutions see greater productivity gains and lower misinformation risks ([[6]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Gartner%20research%20backs%20up%20the,context%20to%20improve%20AI%20results "Highlights: Gartner research backs up the,context to improve AI results")). They advise appointing context engineering leads and creating architecture that continually integrates fresh data ([[25]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Only%20by%20making%20context%20engineering,Gartner%20recommends%20that%20AI%20leaders "Highlights: Only by making context engineering,Gartner recommends that AI leaders")) ([[7]](https://www.gartner.com/en/documents/6904266#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20becoming%20critical,efficiency%20and%20continuous%20context%20validation "Highlights: Context engineering is becoming critical,efficiency and continuous context validation")).
* **Karpathy and Industry Leaders:** OpenAI’s Ash Ashutosh the Pinecone team also emphasized that hallucinations often stem from poor context. Andrej Karpathy famously quipped that *“Context engineering is the delicate art and science of filling the context window with just the right information for the next step.”* ([[26]](https://github.com/davidkimai/Context-Engineering#:~:text=,context%20design%2C%20orchestration%2C%20and%20optimization "Highlights: ,context design, orchestration, and optimization")). In a viral tweet, Tobi Lutke (Shopify CEO) said we should prefer *“context engineering”* to describe the skill of giving the model everything needed to solve the task ([[4]](https://blog.getzep.com/what-is-context-engineering/#:~:text=The%20change%20has%20gotten%20attention,the%20LLM%20can%20solve%20it "Highlights: The change has gotten attention,the LLM can solve it")). These endorsements signal a consensus shift in terminology and thinking.
* **Example - RAG vs Prompting:** Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a prime example of context engineering in action. Rather than crafting a bigger prompt, RAG systems retrieve relevant documents from an external corpus and supply them to the LLM as context. Studies show RAG dramatically improves accuracy on knowledge tasks compared to prompt-only approaches, since the model is given up-to-date facts ([[27]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.00079#:~:text=Experiments%20on%20HotpotQA%20show%20that,backbone%20for%20modern%20LLM%20pipelines "Highlights: Experiments on HotpotQA show that,backbone for modern LLM pipelines")). This approach wouldn’t be called “prompt engineering” – it’s clearly about *engineering context*.

**Table 1** (below) highlights some key differences between prompt engineering and context engineering:

| **Aspect** | **Prompt Engineering** | **Context Engineering** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Scope of Action | Crafting the content and wording of prompts (typically one-shot or few-shot instructions) to elicit desired model outputs | Designing pipelines and systems for gathering, filtering, and supplying relevant data to the model before/while it generates output |
| Focus | Short-term, “shallow” conditioning on the model via text instructions | Long-term, “deep” conditioning via data, memory, APIs, and dynamic context |
| [Data Integration](/services/data-engineering-bi) | Limited to static examples in the prompt, specified by the user | Combines multiple data sources (knowledge bases, user profiles, logs, real-time events) into model context ([[2]](https://www.datacamp.com/blog/context-engineering#:~:text=Context%20engineering%20is%20the%20practice,before%20it%20generates%20a%20response "Highlights: Context engineering is the practice,before it generates a response")) ([[28]](https://www.altexsoft.com/blog/model-context-protocol/#:~:text=Model%20Context%20Protocol%C2%A0is%20a%20universal,custom%20integrations%20for%20each%20one "Highlights: Model Context Protocol is a universal,custom integrations for each one")) |
| Model Interaction | Single-step interaction – take user query + prompt, get response | Multi-step or continuous – interact with memory, tools, and end-user iteratively; maintain conversation state ([[29]](https://www.oreilly.com/radar/context-engineering-bringing-engineering-discipline-to-prompts-part-3/#:~:text=,LLM%20calls%20and%20tool%20uses "Highlights: ,LLM calls and tool uses")) ([[30]](https://www.oreilly.com/radar/context-engineering-bringing-engineering-discipline-to-prompts-part-3/#:~:text=We%E2%80%99re%20really%20talking%20about%20a,to%20solve%20a%20task "Highlights: We’re really talking about a,to solve a task")) |
| Dependencies | Primarily relies on the model’s internal knowledge and prompt phrasing | Relies on external systems (databases, APIs, retrieval systems) and possibly multiple agents through standardized protocols ([[28]](https://www.altexsoft.com/blog/model-context-protocol/#:~:text=Model%20Context%20Protocol%C2%A0is%20a%20universal,custom%20integrations%20for%20each%20one "Highlights: Model Context Protocol is a universal,custom integrations for each one")) |
| Engineering Effort | Focus on trial-and-error prompt design by engineers | Requires software engineering: building data pipelines, memory systems, and orchestrating components; often involves teams and processes ([[25]](https://www.gartner.com/en/articles/context-engineering#:~:text=Only%20by%20making%20context%20engineering,Gartner%20recommends%20that%20AI%20leaders "Highlights: Only by making context engineering,Gartner recommends that AI leaders")) ([[30]](https://www.oreilly.com/radar/context-engineering-bringing-engineering-discipline-to-prompts-part-3/#:~:text=We%E2%80%99re%20really%20talking%20about%20a,to%20solve%20a%20task "Highlights: We’re really talking about a,to solve a task")) |

This table underscores that context engineering is broader: it treats working with LLMs like software engineering, not just one-off conversation tweaks.

Components and Techniques in Context Engineering
================================================

Context engineering encompasses a variety of technical mechanisms. Broadly, we can categorize them into several components:

Retrieval and Augmented Generation
----------------------------------

* **Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG):** RAG systems enhance LLM outputs by retrieving relevant documents or facts at runtime. A retrieval module (often using vector embeddings or search indices) fetches information from a large corpus, which is then concatenated into the prompt. This effectively *injects external knowledge* into the model’s context. Context engineering recognizes RAG as a core pattern, often repeatedly retrieving as the conversation progresses. Recent work formulates **context selection** as an optimization: e.g. *Directed Information γ-covering* uses information theory to select just-enough context chunks while avoiding redundancy ([[9]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.00079#:~:text=We%20introduce%20%5Ctextbf%7BDirected%20Information%20%24%5Cgamma%24,and%20enforces%20a%20diversity%20margin "Highlights: We introduce \textbf{Directed Information $\gamma$,and enforces a diversity margin")). Experiments show such intelligent selection beats naive baselines (like BM25 search) and improves tasks like QA ([[27]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.00079#:~:text=Experiments%20on%20HotpotQA%20show%20that,backbone%20for%20modern%20LLM%20pipelines "Highlights: Experiments on HotpotQA show that,backbone for modern LLM pipelines")).
* **Memory-Augmented Models:** Beyond retrieving static documents, engineers give models a form of memory. This can be **latent memory** (e.g. additional parameters or external memory modules) or **explicit memory** (storing past interactions). For example, *M+* extends the MemoryLLM approach by integrating a retriever with long-term memory, boosting a model’s knowledge retention from 20K to over 160K tokens ([[19]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.00592#:~:text=augmented%20model%20based%20on%20MemoryLLM,tokens%20with%20similar%20GPU%20memory "Highlights: augmented model based on MemoryLLM,tokens with similar GPU memory")). Other architectures compress conversation history into “memory tokens” that travel in the model’s activations. The **R³Mem** architecture compresses long histories and allows exact reconstruction of past context via a reversible process ([[31]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.15957#:~:text=Memory%20plays%20a%20key%20role,For%20retrieval "Highlights: Memory plays a key role,For retrieval")). These memory techniques are engineered to make past context continuously available to the LLM.
* **Knowledge Graphs and Structured Data:** Context engineering often leverages structured knowledge. For example, linking user queries through a knowledge graph can surface related entities and facts that should be included in context. Zep’s Graphiti is an open-source knowledge graph engine gaining traction (14K+ GitHub stars in eight months) as a context layer for AI assistants ([[32]](https://blog.getzep.com/what-is-context-engineering/#:~:text=Graphiti%20knowledge%20graph%20engine%20at,com%2Fgetzep%2Fgraphiti "Highlights: Graphiti knowledge graph engine at,com/getzep/graphiti")). It embodies the idea of “stock the pantry” – encoding enterprise data into a traversable context graph that agents can query. Projects like HippoRAG 2 combine RAG with graph structures (e.g. Personalized PageRank on passage graphs) to better mimic human-like associative memory ([[33]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.14802#:~:text=Our%20ability%20to%20continuously%20acquire%2C,more%20basic%20factual%20memory%20tasks "Highlights: Our ability to continuously acquire,,more basic factual memory tasks")) ([[34]](https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.14802#:~:text=and%20propose%20HippoRAG%202%2C%20a,to%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20human "Highlights: and propose HippoRAG 2, a,to the effectiveness of human")).
* **Tool Integration:** Many context engineering solutions enable the LLM to use tools (calculators, code interpreters, etc.) as context. The **Model Context Protocol (MCP)**, originally developed by Anthropic, defines standard APIs so any tool can be plugged into an AI system ([[28]](https://www.altexsoft.com/blog/model-context-protocol/#:~:text=Model%20Context%20Protocol%C2%A0is%20a%20universal,custom%20integrations%20for%20each%20one "Highlights: Model Context Protocol is a universal,custom integrations for each one")) ([[35]](https://www.altexsoft.com/blog/model-context-protocol/#:~:text=Anthropic%20launched%20MCP%20in%20November,and%20consumed%20by%20AI%20agents "Highlights: Anthropic launched MCP in November,and consumed by AI agents")). In December 2025, Anthropic donated MCP to the **Agentic AI Foundation (AAIF)** under the Linux Foundation, co-founded with Block and OpenAI and backed by Google, Microsoft, AWS, and Cloudflare ([[8]](https://www.anthropic.com/news/donating-the-model-context-protocol-and-establishing-of-the-agentic-ai-foundation)). This governance shift solidified MCP as the universal industry standard, with over 97 million monthly SDK downloads and 75+ official connectors by early 2026. MCP acts as a *translator* and *connector*, akin to HTTP for APIs ([[36]](https://www.altexsoft.com/blog/model-context-protocol/#:~:text=Think%20of%20MCP%20as%3A "Highlights: Think of MCP as:")). OpenAI’s Agents SDK, Google’s AI tools, and Microsoft’s Copilot platform have all adopted MCP, demonstrating industry-wide convergence on unified context access ([[35]](https://www.altexsoft.com/blog/model-context-protocol/#:~:text=Anthropic%20launched%20MCP%20in%20November,and%20consumed%20by%20AI%20agents "Highlights: Anthropic launched MCP in November,and consumed by AI agents")).

